<p>Merlot displays a <strong>deep ruby to garnet color</strong>, with younger wines showing vibrant purple edges that evolve to brick-orange hues with age. The wine typically exhibits medium to full body with <strong>moderate viscosity</strong>—you'll notice gentle legs forming on the glass, indicating the wine's glycerol content and alcohol level, usually ranging from 13.5-15% ABV.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Aromatic Complexity</h3>

<p>Merlot's nose reveals layers of complexity across three aromatic categories. <strong>Primary fruit aromas</strong> dominate with black cherry, plum, and blackberry, often accompanied by red fruit notes like raspberry in cooler climates. <strong>Secondary fermentation aromas</strong> contribute chocolate, vanilla, and sweet baking spices when aged in oak, plus subtle floral violet notes—a hallmark of quality Merlot. <strong>Tertiary aging aromas</strong> develop into leather, tobacco, cedar, and earthy forest floor characteristics in mature bottles.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Palate Profile and Mouthfeel</h3>

<p>On the palate, Merlot showcases <strong>medium to high acidity</strong> that provides freshness without overwhelming the fruit. The tannin structure is notably <strong>softer and more approachable</strong> than Cabernet Sauvignon, with silky, rounded tannins that coat the mouth gently. This creates Merlot's signature velvety texture that wine professionals describe as "plush" or "supple."</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Flavor Spectrum</h3>

<p>The flavor profile mirrors the aromatic complexity: <strong>dark stone fruits</strong> like plum and black cherry dominate, supported by mocha, dark chocolate, and warming spices including cinnamon and clove. Terroir significantly influences secondary flavors—Right Bank Bordeaux Merlots show mineral graphite and wet stone, while warmer New World regions contribute jammy fruit concentration and vanilla oak integration.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700 mb-4">Finish and Quality Markers</h3>

<p>Premium Merlots deliver a <strong>long, persistent finish</strong> lasting 30-45 seconds, with flavors evolving from fruit to spice to earth. Quality indicators include balanced integration of oak (never overwhelming the fruit), seamless tannin structure, and <strong>aromatic complexity that continues developing</strong> in the glass. The finest examples show what sommeliers call "completeness"—no single element dominates, creating harmonious balance between fruit, structure, and terroir expression.</p>

