  <li><strong>Identify Right Bank vs. Left Bank Merlot Character</strong> - Right Bank Bordeaux merlots (Pomerol, Saint-Émilion) showcase merlot's clay-driven elegance with concentrated dark fruit and mineral complexity, while Left Bank versions blend seamlessly with cabernet sauvignon for structure. Look for the telltale iron-rich earthiness in Pomerol versus the limestone-driven freshness of Saint-Émilion to understand merlot's terroir expression.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve at Precisely 60-65°F for Optimal Fruit Expression</strong> - Merlot's supple tannins and prominent fruit flavors shine best when served slightly cooler than cabernet sauvignon. Too warm (above 68°F) and the alcohol overwhelms the delicate plum and cherry notes; too cold (below 58°F) and you'll miss the variety's signature velvety mouthfeel that makes it so approachable.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Young, Premium Merlots for 45-60 Minutes</strong> - While merlot is often praised for immediate drinkability, high-quality examples under 5 years old benefit significantly from moderate aeration. The decanting process allows merlot's naturally lower tannin structure to integrate with its fruit components, revealing secondary notes of cocoa and spice that might otherwise remain muted.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy-Style Glasses for Cooler Climate Merlots</strong> - Washington State, Northern Italian, and cooler vintage Bordeaux merlots express more subtle aromatics that require a wider bowl to concentrate delicate violet, herb, and mineral notes. Reserve larger Bordeaux glasses for warmer climate, fruit-forward merlots from California or Australia where bold fruit needs room to breathe.</li>

