<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Merlot's aging potential varies dramatically based on quality, structure, and origin. <strong>Premium Right Bank Bordeaux</strong> from Pomerol and Saint-Émilion can evolve gracefully for 20-30 years, while high-end California Merlots typically peak between 10-15 years. Entry-level Merlots are best consumed within 2-4 years of vintage.</p>

<h3>Peak Drinking Windows</h3>
<p>Most Merlots follow predictable maturation patterns. <strong>Bordeaux Right Bank</strong> wines show primary fruit for 3-5 years, then enter an awkward "dumb phase" before reopening at 8-12 years with enhanced complexity. Washington State Merlots from Columbia Valley typically drink beautifully at 5-8 years, while softer styles from regions like Chile and Argentina are most approachable at 2-5 years.</p>

<h3>Evolution in the Bottle</h3>
<p>As Merlot ages, its characteristic <strong>plush tannins soften further</strong>, creating silky textures that distinguish well-aged examples. Primary black cherry and plum flavors evolve into complex notes of leather, tobacco, dried herbs, and forest floor. The wine's color shifts from deep ruby to garnet with brick-orange edges—a positive sign of proper development.</p>

<h3>Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>
<p>Store Merlot at a consistent <strong>55-58°F (13-14°C)</strong> with 60-70% humidity. Keep bottles horizontal to maintain cork contact, and protect from light and vibration. Merlot's moderate tannin structure makes it slightly more sensitive to temperature fluctuations than Cabernet Sauvignon.</p>

<h3>Aging vs. Spoilage</h3>
<p>Properly aged Merlot develops <strong>tertiary aromatics</strong>—earthy, savory notes that complement rather than mask the fruit. Warning signs of deterioration include vinegar aromas, excessive browning in young wines, or complete loss of fruit character. Well-cellared Merlot should maintain a core of fruit even at full maturity, distinguishing successful aging from mere oxidation.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
