    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I identify a high-quality Merlot worth aging?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Merlots with firm tannin structure, bright acidity, and complex aromatics beyond simple fruit—think cedar, tobacco, graphite, or violet notes. Premium examples from cooler climates like Washington's Red Mountain or Bordeaux's Pomerol show restrained alcohol levels (under 14.5%) and mineral undertones. Avoid overly jammy, high-alcohol versions that lack structure, as these are best consumed within 3-5 years rather than cellared.</p>
  </div>

